To analyze what it did, we can start from how it print and read. From testing, it read 32 characters(which is the length of flag). And we know that the input is store in v1[273] ~ v1[304]. It&#39;s basicly a NAND machine. From what we got after stimulate the program, we can see 32 &#39;blocks&#39; and each blocks got four  &lt;code&gt;NAND&lt;/code&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img loading=&#34;lazy&#34; data-src=&#34;VM/blocks.png&#34; alt=&#34;VM&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5 id=&#34;thats-what-we-got&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#thats-what-we-got&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; That&#39;s what we got:&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;d_1 = ((a nand b) nand b) nand ((a nand b) nand b) 
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All of them make  &lt;code&gt;xor&lt;/code&gt; . Go back to the main vm_run function, here&#39;s what the rest of the case do:&lt;/p&gt;
